# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: font-loading-strategy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] The **`FontFace`** interface of the CSS Font Loading API represents a single usable font face.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] This interface defines the source of a font face, either a URL to an external resource or a buffer, and font properties such as `style`, `weight`, and so on.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] For URL font sources it allows authors to trigger when the remote font is fetched and loaded, and to track loading status.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] Constructs and returns a new `FontFace` object, built from an external resource described by a URL or from an `ArrayBuffer`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *ascent metric* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `ascent-override` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *descent metric* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `descent-override` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that determines how a font face is displayed based on whether and when it is downloaded and ready to use.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *family* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `font-family` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets infrequently used font features that are not available from a font's variant properties.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the CSS `font-feature-settings` property.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *line-gap metric* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `line-gap-override` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with the current `FontFace` object when the font specified in the object's constructor is done loading or rejects with a `SyntaxError` `DOMException`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] Returns an enumerated value indicating the status of the font, one of `"unloaded"`, `"loading"`, `"loaded"`, or `"error"`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets how the font *stretches*.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `font-stretch` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *style* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `font-style` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *range of unicode code points* encompassing the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `unicode-range` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *variant* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that retrieves or sets the *variation settings* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `font-variation-settings` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] A string that contains the *weight* of the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] It is equivalent to the `font-weight` descriptor.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] Loads a font based on current object's constructor-passed requirements, including a location or source buffer, and returns a `Promise` that resolves with the current FontFace object.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] The code below defines a font face using data at the URL "my-font.woff" with a few font descriptors.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] Just to show how it works, we then define the `stretch` descriptor using a property.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] Next we load the font using `FontFace.load()` and use the returned promise to track completion or report an error.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] To actually *use* the font we will need to add it to a `FontFaceSet`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] We could do that before or after loading the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/api-fontface] For additional examples see CSS Font Loading API > Examples.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] The **`@font-face`** CSS at-rule specifies a custom font with which to display text; the font can be loaded from either a remote server or a locally-installed font on the user's own computer.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Defines the descent metric for the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Determines how a font face is displayed based on whether and when it is downloaded and ready to use.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Specifies a name that will be used as the font face value for font properties.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] A `font-family` name is required for the `@font-face` rule to be valid.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Allows control over advanced typographic features in OpenType fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Allows low-level control over OpenType or TrueType font variations, by specifying the four-letter axis names of the features to vary, along with their variation values.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Defines the line gap metric for the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Defines a multiplier for glyph outlines and metrics associated with this font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] This makes it easier to harmonize the designs of various fonts when rendered at the same font size.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Specifies references to font resources including hints about the font format and technology.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] A `src` is required for the `@font-face` rule to be valid.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] The range of Unicode code points to be used from the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] It's common to use both `url()` and `local()` together, so that the user's installed copy of the font is used if available, falling back to downloading a copy of the font if it's not found on the user's device.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] If the `local()` function is provided, specifying a font name to look for on the user's device, and if the user agent finds a match, that local font is used.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Otherwise, the font resource specified using the `url()` function is downloaded and used.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Browsers attempt to load resources in their list declaration order, so usually `local()` should be written before `url()`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] Both functions are optional, so a rule block containing only one or more `local()` without `url()` is possible.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] If more specific fonts with `format()` or `tech()` values are desired, these should be listed *before* versions that don't have these values, as the less specific variant would otherwise be tried and used first.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] For web delivery, it's generally best to serve fonts in WOFF2 format, because it compresses fonts more efficiently than older formats like WOFF or OpenType, reducing file size and improving load times.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] WOFF2 is also well supported in modern browsers, making it a safe default choice for most websites.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] By allowing authors to provide their own fonts, `@font-face` makes it possible to design content without being limited to the so-called "web-safe" fonts (that is, the fonts that are so common that they're considered to be universally available).
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] The ability to specify the name of a locally-installed font to look for and use makes it possible to customize the font beyond the basics while making it possible to do so without relying on an internet connection.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-face] The `@font-face` at-rule may be used not only at the top level of a CSS, but also inside any CSS conditional-group at-rule.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The **CSS Font Loading API** provides events and interfaces for dynamically loading font resources.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] CSS stylesheets allow authors to use custom fonts; specifying fonts to download using the `@font-face` rule, and applying them to elements with the `font-family` property.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The point at which a font is downloaded is controlled by the user agent.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Most agents only fetch and load fonts when they are first needed, which can result in a perceptible delay.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The CSS Font Loading API overcomes this problem by letting authors control and track when a font face is fetched and loaded, and when it is added to the font face set owned by the document or worker.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Adding a font face to the document or worker font face set allows the user agent to fetch and load the associated font resource automatically if needed.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] A font face can be loaded either before or after it is added to a font face set, but it *must* be added to the set before it can be used for drawing.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Font faces are defined in `FontFace` objects, which specify a binary or URL font source and other properties of font in much the same way as the CSS `@font-face` rule.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] `FontFace` objects are added to the document or worker `FontFaceSet` using `Document.fonts` and `WorkerGlobalScope.fonts`, respectively.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Authors can trigger download of fonts using either `FontFace` or `FontFaceSet`, and monitor loading completion.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] `FontFaceSet` can additionally be used to determine when all fonts required by a page have loaded and the document layout is complete.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The `FontFace.status` property indicates the font face loading status: `unloaded`, `loading`, `loaded` or `failed`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] It is set to `loading` when the file is being downloaded or the font data is being processed, and to `failed` if the font definition is invalid or the font data cannot be loaded.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The status is set to `loaded` when the font face data has been successfully fetched (if needed) and loaded.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Font faces are created using the `FontFace` constructor, which takes as parameters: the font family, the font source, and optional descriptors.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The format and grammar of these arguments is the same as the equivalent `@font-face` definition.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The font source can either be binary data in an `ArrayBuffer` or a font resource at a URL.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] A typical font face definition using a URL source might be as shown below.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Note that the `url()` function is required for URL font sources.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Font faces with a *binary source* are automatically loaded if the font definition is valid and the font data can be loaded — `FontFace.status` is set to `loaded` on success and `failed` otherwise.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Font faces with a URL source are validated but not automatically loaded — `FontFace.status` is set `unloaded` if the font face definition is valid and `failed` otherwise.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Font faces are usually added to the document or worker `FontFaceSet` to allow the user agent to automatically load the font when needed, and *must* be added in order for the font to be used for rendering text.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The code below shows a font face being added to the document.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] A font face can be loaded manually by calling `FontFace.load()`, or by calling `FontFaceSet.load()` if the font face has been added to the `FontFaceSet`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Note that attempting to load an already-loaded font has no effect.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The code below shows how to define a font face, add it to the document fonts, and then initiate a font load.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Note that the `font.load()` returns a promise, so we could have handled the completion of font loading by chaining `then` afterwards.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Using `document.fonts.ready` can be better in some circumstances, as it is only called when all fonts in the document have been resolved and layout is complete.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] An interface loading font faces and checking their download statuses.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] This is a very simple example that shows a font being loaded from Google Fonts and used to draw text to a canvas.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The example also logs the `status` immediately after creation and after loading.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] This code defines a canvas for drawing to and a textarea for logging.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] First we get the element to which we will log, and the canvas that will be used to render text in the downloaded font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Next we define a `FontFace` that has a URL source that is a Google Font and add it to `document.fonts`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] We then log the font status, which should be `unloaded`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Then we call the `FontFace.load()` method to load the font face, and wait on the returned promise.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Once the promise resolves we log the loaded status (which should be `loaded`) and draw text in the loaded font to the canvas.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Note that we could also have waited on the promise returned by the `FontFace.loaded` property, or on `FontFaceSet.ready`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] It should show the name of the font drawn on the canvas in the downloaded font, and a log showing the load status before and after loading.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] This example is similar to the previous one, except that it uses `FontFaceSet.load()` to load the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] It also demonstrates how to listen for font loading events.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The code below defines a canvas context for drawing text, defines a font face, and adds it to the document font face set.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Next we use `load()` on the font face set to load the font, specifying which of the fonts to load.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] If the promise is resolved we use the font to draw some text.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Instead of waiting on a promise we might instead use events to track the font loading operation.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The code below listens for the `loading` and `loadingerror` events and logs the number of font faces for each case.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] In the `loadingdone` event listener we additionally iterate through the font faces and log the family names.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The last bit of code demonstrates how you can monitor the completion of font loading using the promise returned by `FontFaceSet.ready`.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] Unlike the other mechanisms this returns when all fonts defined in the document have been downloaded and layout is complete.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] When the promise resolves we iterate the values in the document's font faces.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] The output below shows the text drawn in "Oxygen" font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/css-font-loading-api] This also shows logging from the events and when the promise returned by `document.fonts.ready` resolves.
[src:font-loading-strategy/font-display] The **`font-display`** descriptor for the `@font-face` at-rule determines how a font face is displayed based on whether and when it is downloaded and ready to use.
[src:font-loading-strategy/font-display] The font display strategy is defined by the user agent.
[src:font-loading-strategy/font-display] Gives the font face a short block period and an infinite swap period.
[src:font-loading-strategy/font-display] Gives the font face an extremely small block period and an infinite swap period.
[src:font-loading-strategy/font-display] Gives the font face an extremely small block period and a short swap period.
[src:font-loading-strategy/font-display] Gives the font face an extremely small block period and no swap period.
[src:font-loading-strategy/font-display] The font display timeline is based on a timer that begins the moment the user agent attempts to use a given downloaded font face.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] The **Web Open Font Format** (**WOFF**) is a font format for use in web pages.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] WOFF files are OpenType or TrueType fonts, with format-specific compression applied and additional XML metadata added.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] The two primary goals are first to distinguish font files intended for use as web fonts from fonts files intended for use in desktop applications via local installation, and second to reduce web font latency when fonts are transferred from a server to a client over a network connection.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] The first draft of WOFF 1 was published in 2009 by Jonathan Kew, Tal Leming, and Erik van Blokland, with reference conversion code written by Jonathan Kew.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Following the submission of WOFF to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) by the Mozilla Foundation, Opera Software and Microsoft in April 2010, the W3C commented that it expected WOFF to soon become the "single, interoperable [font] format" supported by all browsers.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] The W3C published WOFF as a working draft in July 2010.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] The final draft was published as a W3C Recommendation on 13 December 2012.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] WOFF 2.0 significantly improved compression efficiency compared to WOFF 1.0, primarily through the introduction of Brotli, a new byte-level compression algorithm developed by Jyrki Alakuijala and Zoltan Szabadka.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Brotli's effectiveness led to its widespread adoption, notably for HTTP content encoding.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] WOFF 2.0 was standardized as a W3C Recommendation in March 2018, with Google providing the reference implementation.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Each version of the format has received the backing of many type foundries.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] WOFF is a wrapper containing SFNT-based fonts (TrueType or OpenType) that have been compressed using a WOFF-specific encoding tool so they can be embedded in a Web page.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] WOFF Version 1 uses the widely available zlib compression (specifically, the compress2 function), typically resulting in a file size reduction for TrueType files of over 40%.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Since OpenType CFF files (with PostScript glyph outlines) are already compressed, their reduction is typically smaller.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Some browsers enforce a same-origin policy, preventing WOFF fonts from being used across different domains.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] This restriction is part of the CSS 3 Fonts module, where it applies to all font formats and can be overridden by the server providing the font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Some servers may require the manual addition of WOFF's MIME type to serve the files correctly.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Since February 2017, the proper MIME type is `font/woff` for WOFF 1.0 and `font/woff2` for WOFF 2.0.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-open-font-format] Prior to February 2017, the standard MIME type for WOFF 1.0 was `application/font-woff`, and some applications may still use the old type, though it is now deprecated.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] When HTML was first created, typefaces and styles were controlled exclusively by the settings of each web browser.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] There was no mechanism for individual Web pages to control font display until Netscape introduced the `font` element in 1995, which was then standardized in the HTML 3.2 specification.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] However, the computer font specified by the `font` element had to be installed on the user's computer or a fallback font, such as a browser's default sans-serif or monospace font, would be used.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The first CSS specification was published in 1996 and provided the same capabilities.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The CSS2 specification was released in 1998 and attempted to improve the font selection process by adding font matching, synthesis and download.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] These techniques did not gain much use, and were removed in the CSS2.1 specification.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] However, Internet Explorer added support for the font downloading feature in version 4.0, released in 1997.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Font downloading was later included in the CSS3 fonts module, and has since been implemented in Safari 3.1, Opera 10 and Mozilla Firefox 3.5.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] This has subsequently increased interest in Web typography, as well as the use of font downloading.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] All fonts were identified solely by name.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Beyond the properties mentioned above, designers had no way to style fonts, and no mechanism existed to select fonts not present on the client system.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] To ensure that all Web users had a basic set of fonts, Microsoft started the Core fonts for the Web initiative in 1996 (terminated in 2002).
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Released fonts include Arial, Courier New, Times New Roman, Comic Sans, Impact, Georgia, Trebuchet, Webdings and Verdana—under an EULA that made them freely distributable but also limited some rights to their use.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Their high penetration rate has made them a staple for Web designers.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] However, most Linux distributions don't include these fonts by default.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] CSS2 attempted to increase the tools available to Web developers by adding font synthesis, improved font matching and the ability to download remote fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Some CSS2 font properties were removed from CSS2.1 and later included in CSS3.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The CSS specification allows for multiple fonts to be listed as fallback fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The first font specified is the preferred font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] If this font is not available, the Web browser attempts to use the next font in the list.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] If none of the fonts specified are found, the browser displays its default font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] This same process also happens on a per-character basis if the browser tries to display a character not present in the specified font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] To give Web designers some control over the appearance of fonts on their Web pages, even when the specified fonts are not available, the CSS specification allows the use of several generic font families.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] These families are designed to split fonts into several categories based on their general appearance.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] They are commonly specified as the last in a series of fallback fonts, as a last resort in the event that none of the fonts specified by the author are available.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Fonts that do not have decorative markings, or serifs, on their letters.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] These fonts are often considered easier to read on screens.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Fonts that have decorative markings, or serifs, present on their characters.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] These fonts are traditionally used in printed books.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Fonts in which all characters are equally wide.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] These fonts may have a decorative appearance, but they can be difficult to read at small sizes, so they are generally used sparingly.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Fonts that may contain symbols or other decorative properties, but still represent the specified character.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] As of February 2024, the CSS Working Group of W3C proposes that systems specify a default font using `ui` tags; as of the same date, these are not widely supported yet.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] A technique to refer to and automatically download remote fonts was first specified in the CSS2 specification, which introduced the `@font-face` construct.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] At the time, fetching font files from the web was controversial because fonts meant to be used only for certain web pages could also be downloaded and installed in breach of the font license.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Microsoft first added support for downloadable EOT fonts in Internet Explorer 4 in 1997.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Authors had to use the proprietary WEFT tool to create a subsetted font file for each page.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] EOT showed that webfonts could work and the format saw some use in writing systems not supported by common operating systems.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] However, the format never gained widespread acceptance and was ultimately rejected by W3C.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] In 2006, Håkon Wium Lie started a campaign against using EOT and rather have web browsers support commonly used font formats.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Support for the commonly used TrueType and OpenType font formats has since been implemented in Safari 3.1, Opera 10, Mozilla Firefox 3.5 and Internet Explorer 9.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] In 2010, the WOFF compression method for TrueType and OpenType fonts was submitted to W3C by the Mozilla Foundation, Opera Software and Microsoft, and browsers have since added support.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Google Fonts was launched in 2010 to serve webfonts under open-source licenses.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] By 2016, more than 800 webfont families are available.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Webfonts have become an important tool for web designers and as of 2016 a majority of sites use webfonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] By using a specific CSS `@font-face` embedding technique it is possible to embed fonts such that they work with IE4+, Firefox 3.5+, Safari 3.1+, Opera 10+ and Chrome 4.0+.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] This allows the vast majority of Web users to access this functionality.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Some commercial foundries object to the redistribution of their fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Instead, Hoefler & Co. offer a proprietary font delivery system rooted in the cloud.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Many other commercial type foundries address the redistribution of their fonts by offering a specific license, known as a web font license, which permits the use of the font software to display content on the web, a use normally prohibited by basic desktop licenses.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Naturally this does not interfere with fonts and foundries under free licences.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] TrueDoc, while not specifically a webfont specification, was the first standard for embedding fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] It was developed by the type foundry Bitstream in 1994, and became natively supported in Netscape Navigator 4, in 1996.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Due to open source license restrictions, with Netscape unable to release Bitstream's source code, native support for the technology ended when Netscape Navigator 6 was released.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] An ActiveX plugin was available to add support for TrueDoc to Internet Explorer, but the technology had to compete against Microsoft's Embedded OpenType fonts, which had natively supported in their Internet Explorer browser since version 4.0.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Another impediment was the lack of open-source or free tool to create webfonts in TrueDoc format, whereas Microsoft made available a free Web Embedding Fonts Tool to create webfonts in their format.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Internet Explorer has supported font embedding through the proprietary Embedded OpenType standard since version 4.0.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] It uses digital rights management techniques to help prevent fonts from being copied and used without a license.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The SVG specification lets CSS apply to SVG documents in a similar manner to HTML documents, and the `@font-face` rule can be applied to text in SVG documents.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Opera added support for this in version 10, and WebKit since version 325 also supports this method using SVG fonts only.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] SVG fonts was a W3C standard of fonts using SVG graphic that became a subset of OpenType fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] It allowed multicolor or animated fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] It was first a subset of SVG 1.1 specifications but it has been deprecated in the SVG 2.0 specification.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The SVG fonts as independent format is supported by most browsers apart from IE and Firefox, and is deprecated in Chrome (and Chromium).
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] That's now generally deprecated; the standard that most browser vendor agreed with is SVG font subset included in OpenType (and then WOFF superset, see below), called SVGOpenTypeFonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Firefox has supported SVG OpenType since Firefox 26.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Linking to industry-standard *TrueType* (TTF) and *OpenType* (TTF/OTF) fonts is supported by Mozilla Firefox 3.5+, Opera 10+, Safari 3.1+, and Google Chrome 4.0+.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Internet Explorer 9+ supports only those fonts with embedding permissions set to installable.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The Web Open Font Format (WOFF) is essentially OpenType or TrueType with compression and additional metadata.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] WOFF is supported by Mozilla Firefox 3.6+, Google Chrome 5+, Opera Presto, and is supported by Internet Explorer 9 (since March 14, 2011).
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Support is available on Mac OS X Lion's Safari from release 5.1.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The term *Unicode font* is a computer font that maps glyphs to code points defined in the Unicode Standard.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] The term has become redundant since the vast majority of modern computer fonts use Unicode mappings, even those fonts which only include glyphs for a single writing system, or even only support the basic Latin alphabet.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Only two fonts available by default on the Windows platform, Microsoft Sans Serif and Lucida Sans Unicode, provide a wide Unicode character repertoire.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] On free and open-source software platforms such as Linux, GNU Unifont and GNU FreeFont provide a wide range of characters.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] A common hurdle in Web design is the design of mockups that include fonts that are not Web-safe.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] There are a number of solutions for situations like this.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] One common solution is to replace the text with a similar Web-safe font or use a series of similar-looking fallback fonts.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Another technique is *image replacement*.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] This practice involves overlaying text with an image containing the same text written in the desired font.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] This is good for aesthetic purposes, but prevents text selection, increases bandwidth use, is bad for search engine optimization, and makes the text inaccessible for users with disabilities.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] In the past, Flash-based solutions such as sIFR were used.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] This is similar to image replacement techniques, though the text is selectable and rendered as a vector.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] However, this method requires the presence of a proprietary plugin on a client's system.
[src:font-loading-strategy/web-typography] Another solution is using JavaScript to replace the text with VML (for Internet Explorer) or SVG (for all other browsers).
